    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, i'm studying for my checkride and i'm a bit confused about pitot tubes. can u explain how they actually work to measure airspeed? specifically how the pressure difference creates the reading?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure thing! Pitot tubes are a bit like the nose of a flying bird, they measure the airspeed by comparing the pressure of the air flowing into the tube with the static air pressure outside. Imagine a little pitot tube as a tiny, invisible nose that sticks out into the wind. As the wind rushes past, it creates a pressure difference inside the tube, which is then compared to the static air pressure outside. This pressure difference is what tells us the airspeed. It's like having a tiny, invisible pitot tube on your nose, and it tells you how fast you're flying by comparing the wind pressure on your nose to the calm air pressure outside. So, the pitot tube is essentially measuring the difference in air pressure to give you the airspeed reading. It's a bit like how a bird can sense the wind pressure on its wings to know how fast it's flying.",
      "source": "target",
