    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, pitot tubes can indeed get blocked, and it's not just the weather that can cause issues. Imagine a little pitot tube as a tiny, invisible nose that sticks out into the wind. If something like ice, bugs, or even a bit of dirt gets into that nose, it can block the airflow and mess with the pressure reading. It's like if a bird gets a little bit of mud on its wings, it can't fly as well, right? The same goes for a pitot tube. So, it's not just about the weather, but also things like ice, bugs, or even just a bit of dirt that can get into the pitot tube and mess with the airflow, causing the pressure reading to be inaccurate. It's like having a little pitot tube on your nose, and if something gets in the way, it can't sense the wind pressure correctly, which means it can't tell you how fast you're flying. So, it's important to keep the pitot tube clear of any obstructions to ensure accurate airspeed readings.",
